<br>
How does the LDS Church choose a living prophet? Is there a certain criteria that must be met? Is the prophet kind of like the Catholics and the Pope?<br>
<br>
I'm just curious...Thanks! <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>I'm just goofin' on you, baybee!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Cosmo</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=snowgirly>snowgirly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/2/03 9:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Choosing a Prophet</span><hr size=1> Well, I don't know for sure if they have ever come out with a reasoning behind this but each time a Prophet dies, the next prophet has always been the President of the Quorum of the 12. <br>
<br>
The way that the hierarchy of the church is set up is as follows:<br>
Christ is the head, the Prophet is the acting head of our church but he directs the church based on revelation from God and Jesus Christ. He has a 1st and 2nd Counselor. Then there are the Quorum of the 12 Apostles. 12 men who act as apostles to the Lord and who, when making decisions, all have to be in agreement through prayer and fasting. Next comes the Quorums of the Seventies and I believe that there are 3 of those now. As the church grows, there will be need of more because each of the Seventies is responsible for areas of the church. <br>
<br>
Anyway, the President of the Quorum of the 12 has always, as far as I know, been the next prophet. As it stands now, President Gordon B. Hinkley is the Prophet, Thomas S. Monson is 1st Counselor, and James E. Faust is 2nd Counselor. However, there is currently an acting president of the 12 Apostles because Thomas S. Monson is in actuality the President of the Quorum of the 12 however he can't do both jobs. If President Hinkley were to die, Monson would most likely be the next prophet. <br>
<br>
Hope that helps!<br>
Heather <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhinosmom>rhinosmom</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://mjkingbird.homestead.com/files/paige.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/2/03 9:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: LDS! I remembered my question!!!</span><hr size=1> We have the Prophet and the 12 Apostles. Should the Prophet die, the next Prophet would be the President of the Quorum of the 12 Apostles. Essentially, the senior Apostle. It moves through that way.<br>
<br>
That was one of the problems early on in the church after Joseph Smith was murdered, His family felt it should stay within the family, not necessarily whom God has elected. When Brigham Young became the next Prophet and everyone headed west, some people remained and started their own group. For years it was known as RLDS (Re-organized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints), but have since changed their name recently-I'ce drawn a blank. Those people have basically kept it in the Smith Family.  <p>Paige<br>
